          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In pemphigus vulgaris, which structural component of the epidermis is targeted b</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In pemphigus vulgaris, which structural component of the epidermis is targeted by autoantibodies, leading to blister formation?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Hemidesmosomes</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Hemidesmosomes anchor basal cells to the basement membrane. Their destruction causes subepidermal blistering, as seen in bullous pemphigoid — not the intraepidermal splitting of pemphigus vulgaris.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Desmosomes</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. IgG autoantibodies attack desmosomal proteins (desmogleins), destroying the intercellular bridges between keratinocytes. This causes acantholysis — the loss of cell-to-cell adhesion — and intraepidermal blistering.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Tight junctions</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Tight junctions form paracellular permeability barriers in epithelia. They regulate what passes between cells but are not the primary mechanical adhesion structures targeted in pemphigus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Gap junctions</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Gap junctions are channels for intercellular communication (ions, small molecules), not for mechanical adhesion. Their loss would impair cell signalling, not cause blistering.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The video explained that in pemphigus vulgaris, the immune system attacks desmosomes — the molecular anchors between keratinocytes — causing acantholysis and intraepidermal blistering."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! Desmosomes are the molecular anchors holding keratinocytes together, and their autoimmune destruction is the hallmark of pemphigus vulgaris."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
