          },
          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>During karyotyping, colchicine is added to the cell culture. What is its role in</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>During karyotyping, colchicine is added to the cell culture. What is its role in the procedure?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It stimulates lymphocyte division</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Phytohaemagglutinin (PHA), a plant-derived mitogen, is the agent that stimulates lymphocytes to divide. Colchicine acts at a later step, after division has begun.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It blocks spindle formation, arresting cells in metaphase</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Colchicine inhibits microtubule polymerisation, preventing spindle fibre assembly. This arrests dividing cells in metaphase, when chromosomes are maximally condensed and easiest to visualise and identify.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It causes cells to swell so chromosomes spread apart</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Swelling and chromosome spreading are achieved by hypotonic potassium chloride solution, which is applied after colchicine arrest — not by colchicine itself.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It stains chromosomes to produce a banding pattern</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Giemsa stain, used in G-banding, produces the characteristic dark-and-light banding pattern for chromosome identification. Colchicine has no staining role.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The karyotyping sequence is: PHA stimulates division → colchicine arrests at metaphase → hypotonic KCl spreads chromosomes → Giemsa stain identifies them. Colchicine's specific role is metaphase arrest."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! Colchicine halts mitosis at metaphase by disrupting spindle fibres, giving the clearest view of maximally condensed chromosomes."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
